They also serve specialised food for people who are fasting but i believe they serve it on fixed days of the week.  The quality of the food is definitely good and they serve in steel plates (another good thing which i like). This is a typical self service kind of restaurant, but the advantage is self service restro are mostly those places where footfall is more and hence they serve fresh food every time.  They have limited seating area and almost no parking space even for a two wheeler, common parking is available out side at khumthekar road so if you are lucky you would get it. If you are on Laxmi Road and you feel hungry this is atleast a one time visit restaurant. They serve South Indian and Maharashtrian delicacies and that too authentic maharashtrian. Their menu ranges from Dosa, Idli and Uthappa too Misal, Sabudana items and Kothambir wadis. They also serve specialised food for people who are fasting but i believe they serve it on fixed days of the week.  The quality of the food is definitely good and they serve in steel plates (another good thing which i like). This is a typical self service kind of restaurant, but the advantage is self service restro are mostly those places where footfall is more and hence they serve fresh food every time.  They have limited seating area and almost no parking space even for a two wheeler, common parking is available out side at khumthekar road so if you are lucky you would get it.  Their misal is really good and their taste of sambhar is good. Their portion size is i believe is little on a lesser side. Their staff attitude might look little harsh but thats how it is in Sadashiv peth. The ambience and the people and the overall feel would definitely take you to a old golden era in Pune.             {
              "review": {
                "rating": 4,
                "review_text": "A very old typical Sadashiv Peth kind of restaurant. Now you will ask me who gave you right to speak about Sadashiv peth attitude...becoz i myself is a resident of Sadashiv Peth.... If you are on Laxmi Road and you feel hungry this is atleast a one time visit restaurant. They serve South Indian and Maharashtrian delicacies and that too authentic maharashtrian. Their menu ranges from Dosa, Idli and Uthappa too Misal, Sabudana items and Kothambir wadis. They also serve specialised food for people who are fasting but i believe they serve it on fixed days of the week.  The quality of the food is definitely good and they serve in steel plates (another good thing which i like). This is a typical self service kind of restaurant, but the advantage is self service restro are mostly those places where footfall is more and hence they serve fresh food every time.  They have limited seating area and almost no parking space even for a two wheeler, common parking is available out side at khumthekar road so if you are lucky you would get it.  Their misal is really good and their taste of sambhar is good. Their portion size is i believe is little on a lesser side. Their staff attitude might look little harsh but thats how it is in Sadashiv peth. The ambience and the people and the overall feel would definitely take you to a old golden era in Pune. Overall a must visit place atleast once.",

              "review": {
                "rating": 4,
                "review_text": "This place is kind of lost in the glitter & glamour of Sujata, khatri, Rajmandir & naturals but I thought was equally good in terms of taste/ quality of mastani.  Have tried mango, sitafal, chiku, anjeer etc flsvors and found all good.  The only thing is; this is located on kumthekar road at ground floor of a building but not on road front. So you need to 'find' it. Also the staff is laid back & not much in hurry to serve you.  The rates are almost same as any other mastani shop (around 80 rs for mango mastani in beginning of 2019)  You can give this place a try if you don't want to wait in queue for other crowded mastani shops",
                "id": 44579279,
                "rating_color": "5BA829",
                "review_time_friendly": "2 months ago",
                "rating_text": "Great!",
                "timestamp": 1566137433,

              "review": {
                "rating": 4,
                "review_text": "One thing I never liked about the great Sujata Mastani was when in the afternoon, you wanted to try the Mastani you had to sit on few chairs outside the closed Sujata Mastani outlet after you got it from the small joint across the road. VALUE FOR MONEY Pretty decently priced. Two full Mastanis were for Rs. 170.               "review": {
                "rating": 1,
                "review_text": "When you put the name Paratha in your business name then the expectations are set that you have the mastered the art of Parathas. And the litmus test for the same is how well you can make Aloo Paratha.  FOOD ORDERED  [Aloo Paratha]  Dough - The dough was not kneaded well so the paratha was breaking apart.  Stuffing - The stuffing had raw onions and no seasoning.  Butter - The dollop of butter was reeking the fridge smell.  Dahi - The side served was very sour and stale.  Chutney - Made in advance and kept in the fridge which was gradually going down.  AMBIENCE Strictly okay.  SERVICE Okay  VALUE FOR MONEY Don't bother if the food is not up to the mark.  OVERALL EXPERIENCE I have always taken pride in the ventures started by Apla Marathi Manus and so was excited to try the best dishes served by Shiv Paratha House starting with the Aloo Paratha.               "review": {
                "rating": 4,
                "review_text": "I happened to be in the vicinity. Seemed like a reasonable place to grab a bite. And am a hardcore non-vegetarian btw.               "review": {
                "rating": 3,
                "review_text": "Have always craved for Dal Pakwan from Vig, Chembur and when I saw one shop serving the same in Pune near me, i definitely wanted to give it a try.  FOOD ORDERED  Dal Pakwan *** Dal was tasty with balanced flavors. However I missed the tadka. Pakwan was however thin and crispy. Personally, i prefer a thicker one.  Methi Paratha **** Surprisingly, i liked it more than Dal Pakwan. Nice flavor of Methi and prepared with generous oil.  Chutney **** The chutney served with Paratha though watery was too good. Hint of khatta meetha taste.  Gulab Jamun ** Didn't expect much from this sweet. Definitely not a mawa Gulab Jamun.  AMBIENCE It's a small shack so not much of an ambience.  VALUE FOR MONEY All the dishes were very pocket friendly.  OVERALL EXPERIENCE Will revisit for Dal Pakwan and Parathas of course with the unique chutney.",

            {
              "review": {
                "rating": 4,
                "review_text": "A very old typical Sadashiv Peth kind of restaurant. Now you will ask me who gave you right to speak about Sadashiv peth attitude...becoz i myself is a resident of Sadashiv Peth.... If you are on Laxmi Road and you feel hungry this is atleast a one time visit restaurant. They serve South Indian and Maharashtrian delicacies and that too authentic maharashtrian. Their menu ranges from Dosa, Idli and Uthappa too Misal, Sabudana items and Kothambir wadis. They also serve specialised food for people who are fasting but i believe they serve it on fixed days of the week.  The quality of the food is definitely good and they serve in steel plates (another good thing which i like). This is a typical self service kind of restaurant, but the advantage is self service restro are mostly those places where footfall is more and hence they serve fresh food every time.  They have limited seating area and almost no parking space even for a two wheeler, common parking is available out side at khumthekar road so if you are lucky you would get it.  Their misal is really good and their taste of sambhar is good. Their portion size is i believe is little on a lesser side. Their staff attitude might look little harsh but thats how it is in Sadashiv peth. The ambience and the people and the overall feel would definitely take you to a old golden era in Pune. Overall a must visit place atleast once.",

            {
              "review": {
                "rating": 4,
                "review_text": "One thing I never liked about the great Sujata Mastani was when in the afternoon, you wanted to try the Mastani you had to sit on few chairs outside the closed Sujata Mastani outlet after you got it from the small joint across the road. So how was our experience, let's see..  FOOD ORDERED Mango Mastani Surprisingly, it tasted at par with Sujata Mango Mastani if not better. Loved it.  Pista Mastani This one was also very good.  AMBIENCE With just three limited tables, though it was not enough seating but was definitely better than sitting or standing outside while having your Mastani.  VALUE FOR MONEY Pretty decently priced. Two full Mastanis were for Rs. 170.  OVERALL EXPERIENCE While I am a die hard fan of Sujata Mastani, but if I have an option to stand outside and eat or sit inside and enjoy my Mastani under the cool breeze of fan.               "review": {
                "rating": 1,
                "review_text": "When you put the name Paratha in your business name then the expectations are set that you have the mastered the art of Parathas.               "review": {
                "rating": 3,
                "review_text": "Have always craved for Dal Pakwan from Vig, Chembur and when I saw one shop serving the same in Pune near me, i definitely wanted to give it a try. Methi Paratha **** Surprisingly, i liked it more than Dal Pakwan. Nice flavor of Methi and prepared with generous oil.  Chutney **** The chutney served with Paratha though watery was too good. Hint of khatta meetha taste.  Gulab Jamun ** Didn't expect much from this sweet. Definitely not a mawa Gulab Jamun.  AMBIENCE It's a small shack so not much of an ambience.  VALUE FOR MONEY All the dishes were very pocket friendly.  OVERALL EXPERIENCE Will revisit for Dal Pakwan and Parathas of course with the unique chutney.",

              "review": {
                "rating": 3,
                "review_text": "We ordered Sabudana khichadi, Idli Sambar and taak. The khichadi was served with coconut chutney and tasted good. We didn't like the idli sambar much though.             {
              "review": {
                "rating": 4,
                "review_text": "A very old typical Sadashiv Peth kind of restaurant. Now you will ask me who gave you right to speak about Sadashiv peth attitude...becoz i myself is a resident of Sadashiv Peth.... If you are on Laxmi Road and you feel hungry this is atleast a one time visit restaurant. They serve South Indian and Maharashtrian delicacies and that too authentic maharashtrian. Their menu ranges from Dosa, Idli and Uthappa too Misal, Sabudana items and Kothambir wadis. They also serve specialised food for people who are fasting but i believe they serve it on fixed days of the week.  The quality of the food is definitely good and they serve in steel plates (another good thing which i like). This is a typical self service kind of restaurant, but the advantage is self service restro are mostly those places where footfall is more and hence they serve fresh food every time.  They have limited seating area and almost no parking space even for a two wheeler, common parking is available out side at khumthekar road so if you are lucky you would get it.  Their misal is really good and their taste of sambhar is good. Their portion size is i believe is little on a lesser side. Their staff attitude might look little harsh but thats how it is in Sadashiv peth. The ambience and the people and the overall feel would definitely take you to a old golden era in Pune. Overall a must visit place atleast once.",

              "review": {
                "rating": 4,
                "review_text": "This place is kind of lost in the glitter & glamour of Sujata, khatri, Rajmandir & naturals but I thought was equally good in terms of taste/ quality of mastani. So you need to 'find' it. Also the staff is laid back & not much in hurry to serve you.  The rates are almost same as any other mastani shop (around 80 rs for mango mastani in beginning of 2019)  You can give this place a try if you don't want to wait in queue for other crowded mastani shops",

            {
              "review": {
                "rating": 4,
                "review_text": "One thing I never liked about the great Sujata Mastani was when in the afternoon, you wanted to try the Mastani you had to sit on few chairs outside the closed Sujata Mastani outlet after you got it from the small joint across the road. So after having a spicy misal when we went for the Mastani, it was crowded with no empty chairs and this is when we saw the most ignored Kondhalkar Mastani House. So how was our experience, let's see..  FOOD ORDERED Mango Mastani Surprisingly, it tasted at par with Sujata Mango Mastani if not better. Loved it.  Pista Mastani This one was also very good.  AMBIENCE With just three limited tables, though it was not enough seating but was definitely better than sitting or standing outside while having your Mastani.  VALUE FOR MONEY Pretty decently priced. Two full Mastanis were for Rs. 170.  OVERALL EXPERIENCE While I am a die hard fan of Sujata Mastani, but if I have an option to stand outside and eat or sit inside and enjoy my Mastani under the cool breeze of fan.               "review": {
                "rating": 1,
                "review_text": "When you put the name Paratha in your business name then the expectations are set that you have the mastered the art of Parathas. And the litmus test for the same is how well you can make Aloo Paratha.  FOOD ORDERED  [Aloo Paratha]  Dough - The dough was not kneaded well so the paratha was breaking apart.  Stuffing - The stuffing had raw onions and no seasoning.  Butter - The dollop of butter was reeking the fridge smell.  Dahi - The side served was very sour and stale.  Chutney - Made in advance and kept in the fridge which was gradually going down.  AMBIENCE Strictly okay.  SERVICE Okay  VALUE FOR MONEY Don't bother if the food is not up to the mark.  OVERALL EXPERIENCE I have always taken pride in the ventures started by Apla Marathi Manus and so was excited to try the best dishes served by Shiv Paratha House starting with the Aloo Paratha. But to my dismay, the Aloo Paratha served was just pathetic. So will not dare to try again.",

              "review": {
                "rating": 4,
                "review_text": "I happened to be in the vicinity. Seemed like a reasonable place to grab a bite. And am a hardcore non-vegetarian btw. It lacked certain buttery touch to it. And also it should have been cooked more to extract its \"Chhonk\"'s flavor.  Overall, if you are in the locality, must visit! Kudos.",

              "review": {
                "rating": 3,
                "review_text": "Have always craved for Dal Pakwan from Vig, Chembur and when I saw one shop serving the same in Pune near me, i definitely wanted to give it a try.  FOOD ORDERED  Dal Pakwan *** Dal was tasty with balanced flavors. However I missed the tadka. Pakwan was however thin and crispy. Personally, i prefer a thicker one.  Methi Paratha **** Surprisingly, i liked it more than Dal Pakwan. Nice flavor of Methi and prepared with generous oil.  Chutney **** The chutney served with Paratha though watery was too good. Hint of khatta meetha taste.  Gulab Jamun ** Didn't expect much from this sweet. Definitely not a mawa Gulab Jamun.  AMBIENCE It's a small shack so not much of an ambience.  VALUE FOR MONEY All the dishes were very pocket friendly.  OVERALL EXPERIENCE Will revisit for Dal Pakwan and Parathas of course with the unique chutney.",
